Releasing a function with this signature was a mistake:
{code}
mongoc_host_list_t *
mongoc_server_description_host (const mongoc_server_description_t *description)
{code}
The host list should be const.

The {{mongoc_log_func_t}} typedef is used in the parameters of exported function symbols declared with {{\_\_cdecl}} (including {{{}mongoc_log_default_handler{}}}) but is not declared with {{{}\_\_cdecl{}}}, meaning a different default calling convention (e.g. {{\_\_vectorcall}} with {{{}/Gv{}}}) changes the calling convention of the {{mongoc_log_func_t}} type and dependent exported function symbols. This means the following program fails to link with {{{}/Gv{}}}:
{code:cpp}
void broken(void) {
  // error: mongoc_log_default_handler is declared with __cdecl, but due to /Gv,
  //        mongoc_log_set_handler requires a function pointer with __vectorcall
  //        because mongoc_log_func_t is missing __cdecl, so mongoc_log_default_handler
  //        is not considered a valid argument (incompatible pointer types).
  mongoc_log_set_handler(&mongoc_log_default_handler, NULL);
}
{code}

Found by [~chris.cho], of which he included a thorough repro data and code here:
https://gist.github.com/ccho-mongodb/67dc14a2344971619403982def475a8d

Per the auth spec, the username we're deriving from the client certificate should conform to:
{noformat}
openssl x509 -subject -nameopt RFC2253 -noout -inform PEM -in test-client.pem
{noformat}

On the client certificate provided in that gist, that command results in:
{noformat}
CN=Chris,OU=TestClientCertificateOrgUnit,O=EducationClientCertificate,L=TestClientCertificateLocality,ST=TestClientCertificateState,C=US
{noformat}

But the C driver on macOS derives the username as:
{noformat}
C=US,ST=TestClientCertificateState,L=TestClientCertificateLocality,O=EducationClientCertificate,OU=TestClientCertificateOrgUnit,CN=Chris
{noformat}

Which results in an authentication failure. As a workaround, the username can be provided explicitly.

*Proposal:* When a client is pushed back onto the pool, reduce the size of large connection buffers.

*Background & Motivation*

HELP-78501 reports observed memory growth in a long-lived process. This appears to be due to reading large responses on a buffered stream. The long-lived buffered stream does not later reduce the size until the pool is destroyed.

An [example|https://github.com/kevinAlbs/mongo-c-driver/blob/HELP-78501/src/libmongoc/tests/HELP-78501/test-memory-usage.c] creating many cursors reading large responses reproduces the issue. Here is a simplified snippet:
{code:c}
mongoc_client_t *client[100];
for (int i = 0; i < 100; i++) {
    client[i] = mongoc_client_pool_pop (pool);
}

for (int i = 0; i < 100; i++) {
    // Server replies may be 16MB each.
    find_all_documents (client[i], "db", "big_collection");
}

// 1600 MB allocated and will not be freed until `mongoc_client_pool_destroy`.
{code}
macOS Instruments shows many 16MB buffers allocated after calls to \{{find_all_documents}} complete:
!instruments.png|width=294,height=489!

After calling {{{}mongoc_client_pool_destroy{}}}, memory usage lowers to near 0.

The default stream initiator [creates buffered streams|https://github.com/mongodb/mongo-c-driver/blob/aa371fab760eebce88a2627c3b55d7de5fe93c9f/src/libmongoc/src/mongoc/mongoc-client.c#L898-L907].

*Summary*
{{mongoc_collection_create_indexes_with_opts}} uses {{mongoc_client_command_with_opts}} rather than {{mongoc_collection_write_command_with_opts}}. As a result, write command behavior is not applied:
- Write concern is not inherited from the parent {{mongoc_collection_t}}
- A server reply with a "writeConcernError" does not result in a failing return.

*Background & Motivation*

{{mongoc_collection_create_indexes_with_opts}} [documents|https://mongoc.org/libmongoc/1.30.2/mongoc_collection_create_indexes_with_opts.html]:

{quote}If no write concern is provided in opts, the collection’s write concern is used.
{quote}

That appears untrue. When updating the {{create_index}} test function in test-mongoc-opts.c to switch from the deprecated {{mongoc_collection_create_index_with_opts}} to {{mongoc_collection_create_indexes_with_opts}}, the test failed with:

{code}
$ ./cmake-build/src/libmongoc/test-libmongoc -d --no-fork --match "/inheritance/create_index*"

[...]

Expected: { "createIndexes" : "collection", "writeConcern" : { "w" : "collection" } }
, Got: { "createIndexes" : "collection", "indexes" : [ { "key" : { "foo" : "bar" }, "name" : "foo_bar" } ], "$db" : "database", "lsid" : { "id" : { "$binary" : { "base64" : "rZ2NhtrGTSKAmjJJzi9Ang==", "subType" : "04" } } }, "$clusterTime" : { "clusterTime" : { "$timestamp" : { "t" : 1, "i" : 1 } }, "signature" : { "hash" : { "$binary" : { "base64" : "", "subType" : "00" } }, "keyId" : { "$numberLong" : "6446735049323708417" } }, "operationTime" : { "$timestamp" : { "t" : 1, "i" : 1 } } } }
, writeConcern: not found
{code}

Discovered when removing deprecated {{mongoc_collection_create_index_with_opts}} for C driver 2.0.

